@leocnj Three possible solutions you can try:

(1) put the `export LD_LIBRARY_PATH = ...` into `.bashrc`, then logout;

(2) Startup RStudio from terminal by using `/Applications/RStudio.app/Contents/MacOS/RStudio`;

(3) use `Sys.setenv` in RStudio before you load mxnet.

here is code in infershape:

``` C
    oshape[2] = std::min(dshape[2] + 2 * param_.pad[0] - param_.kernel[0] + param_.stride[0] - 1,
                         dshape[2] + 2 * param_.pad[0] - 1) / param_.stride[0] + 1;
    oshape[3] = std::min(dshape[3] + 2 * param_.pad[1] - param_.kernel[1] + param_.stride[1] - 1,
                         dshape[3] + 2 * param_.pad[1] - 1) / param_.stride[1] + 1;
    CHECK(oshape[2] > 0 && oshape[3] > 0) << "Pooling: kernel size exceed input";
```

Looks like it crashes in this case unless pad is big enough. Are you padding?

@wangg12 if you take a look at these callbacks, you can find it is not hard to create another closure to pass and push data into a list, for example,

``` python
def log_to_list(period, lst):
    def _callback(param):
        """The checkpoint function."""
        if param.nbatch % period == 0:
            name, value = param.eval_metric.get()
            lst.append(value)
    return _callback
```

I think multiple callbacks can be passed in via a list
